## Coding standards

### Language and runtime

- TypeScript with strict mode
- Node.js >= 20
- ESM modules

### Patterns we follow

<!-- List the patterns the team has agreed on. Be specific. -->

- Repository pattern for data access
- Service layer for business logic (services never import from api/)
- Dependency injection via constructor parameters, not global imports
- Error handling: custom error classes extending AppError, caught by error middleware
- Logging: structured JSON via pino, never console.log in production code

### Patterns we avoid

<!-- Equally important — what should the AI NOT do? -->

- No classes where functions will do
- No ORMs — we use raw SQL with parameterised queries
- No barrel exports (index.ts re-exports)
- No `any` type — use `unknown` and narrow
- No default exports (except where required by framework)

### Naming conventions

- Files: kebab-case (`user-service.ts`)
- Functions/variables: camelCase
- Types/interfaces: PascalCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Database tables: snake_case
- API endpoints: kebab-case (`/api/user-settings`)

### Testing

- Unit tests: colocated (`user-service.test.ts` next to `user-service.ts`)
- Integration tests: `tests/integration/`
- E2E tests: `tests/e2e/`
- Test naming: `should <expected behaviour> when <condition>`
- Prefer testing behaviour over implementation details
- No mocking of internal modules — only external boundaries (DB, APIs, time)

